CN and NH3 are listed as hub intermediates but lack explicit upstream synthesis in this network.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add explicit HCN synthesis from NH3 + CH4 or NH3 + CO (atmospheric chemistry)\", \"Consider UV-driven cyanosulfidic conditions more explicitly\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.92, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_008\": 0.87, \"rxn_006\": 0.88},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n            \"feedback\": \"Excellent convergent pathway that bridges hydrothermal and surface environments. CO2 fixation to pyruvate (Preiner et al., 2020) proceeds hydrothermally, pyruvate thermally decarboxylates to acetaldehyde (a known instability that is cleverly leveraged as a feature), and then Strecker chemistry at the surface completes the synthesis. This directly addresses the literature-noted challenge of pyruvate thermal instability by channeling the decarboxylation product (acetaldehyde) into a productive pathway. The hydrothermal \u2192 surface environmental transition is well-justified: pyruvate decarboxylation occurs at elevated temperature, and products are transported to cooler surface pools for Strecker chemistry. Literature support is strong across all four steps.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Note that pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde competes with productive pyruvate use in P1 \u2014 discuss kinetic partitioning\", \"Consider specifying mineral catalyst for rxn_009\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_007\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\